## What happened

Apple removed DSA support from its cryptographic frameworks. .NET on macOS delegates to those native libraries, so starting in **.NET 11**, `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. Windows and Linux still work because they use OpenSSL/CNG, which still support DSA.

## How to fix it

You have two options:

### Option 1 – Migrate to a modern algorithm (preferred)
Re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** and update your verification code. DSA is considered legacy and weak by modern standards.

### Option 2 – Keep verifying legacy DSA signatures
If you **must** verify existing DSA signatures you can't re-sign, use **BouncyCastle** as a managed (cross-platform) DSA implementation:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

// Load your DSA public key and use BouncyCastle's verifier
var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, dsaPublicKeyParameters);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

This runs entirely in managed code, so it works on all platforms regardless of native OS support.
